related_questions.question: How do I calculate my retirement age?
related_questions.title: AI Overview
list: If you were born between 1943 and 1954, your FRA is 66.
If you were born in 1960 or later, your FRA is 67.

If you were born between 1955 and 1959, your FRA is between 66 and 67, increasing by a few months for each birth year. You can use a Social Security Administration's calculator to find the exact FRA for your birth year.
You can start receiving Social Security benefits as early as age 62, but your monthly benefit will be permanently reduced.
If you wait until your full retirement age, you will receive 100% of your calculated benefit.
You can also delay claiming benefits past your FRA, which will increase your monthly benefit.
Minimum Retirement Age for Federal Employees: . Opens in new tabIf you are a federal employee, there is a minimum retirement age (MRA) that may be different from your FRA.
Personal Savings and Investments: . Opens in new tabYou'll need to consider your personal savings and investments to determine if you have enough to cover your expenses in retirement.
Health and Lifestyle: . Opens in new tabYour health and desired lifestyle will also play a role in when you choose to retire.

related_questions.question: What is the $1000 a month rule for retirement?
related_questions.title: AI Overview
list: The Foundation: The rule is based on the idea that you can safely withdraw 5% of your retirement savings annually and still have your money last for a reasonable period (often considered 20-30 years).
Calculating Savings: To determine your total savings goal, multiply your desired monthly income by 240,000.
Example: If you want $4,000 a month, you'd need $4,000 * $240,000/$1,000 = $960,000.

Considerations: Inflation: The rule doesn't directly account for inflation, so it's important to consider how rising prices might affect your expenses.  Other Income: The rule focuses on savings, but your retirement income might also include Social Security, pensions, or other investments.  Personal Needs: Your individual expenses and lifestyle choices will significantly impact how much you need in retirement, so this is just a guideline.

related_questions.snippet: If you have $400,000 in the bank you can retire early at age 62, but it will be tight. The good news is that if you can keep working for just five more years, you are on track for a potentially quite comfortable retirement by full retirement age.
